<p><b>Human Rights Council 
Twentieth session 
</b></p>
<p>Agenda item 3 
<b>Promotion and protection of all human rights, civil, 
</b></p>
<p><b>political, economic, social and cultural rights, 
</b></p>
<p><b>including the right to development 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Report of the Special Rapporteur on the right of everyone to 
the enjoyment of the highest attainable standard of physical 
and mental health, Anand Grover 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Addendum  
</b></p>
<p><b>  Mission to Ghana</b>*<b> 
</b></p>
<p><i>Summary 
</i></p>
<p>The Special Rapporteur on the right of everyone to the enjoyment of the highest 
attainable standard of physical and mental health, Anand Grover, visited Ghana from 23 to 
30 May 2011. During the mission, he held meetings with Government representatives, civil 
society organizations, health professionals, academics and representatives of local 
communities in Accra, Tamale and Kumasi. 
</p>
<p>The Special Rapporteur commends Ghana on its clear commitment to realizing the 
highest attainable standard of physical and mental health of its citizens. However, a number 
of serious issues exist that need to be addressed in order to fully realize the right to health. 
Furthermore, Ghana&#8217;s recent transition from a low-income to a lower middle-income 
country is likely to present a number of funding issues, potentially threatening the nation&#8217;s 
progress in regard to the right to health. 
</p>
<p>Sections I and II of the report deal with issues regarding Ghana&#8217;s development 
background and legal obligations. In section III, the Special Rapporteur examines the effect 
of the National Health Insurance Scheme (NHIS) on the right to health in Ghana. While the 
development of the NHIS is a commendable step toward ensuring access to quality 
healthcare for all, serious concerns exist regarding membership and coverage, the exclusion 
of some important goods and services, and the long-term sustainability of the NHIS. 
</p>
<p>  
 * The summary of the present report is being circulated in all official languages. The report, which is 
</p>
<p>annexed to the summary, is being circulated in the language of submission only. 
</p>
<p> 
United Nations 
</p>
<p> 
A/HRC/20/15/Add.1  
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p><b>A/HRC/20/15/Add.1  
</b></p>
<p><b>2</b>  
</p>
<p>Section IV focuses on the extreme under-resourcing of the mental health sector in Ghana. 
The country faces several barriers to providing quality mental health care to its citizens, 
including deficiencies in mental health care facilities, shortages in mental health 
practitioners as well as language and physical accessibility barriers. Issues regarding 
women&#8217;s health are examined in section V. Ghana has declared maternal mortality to be a 
&#8220;national emergency&#8221;. While the Government has taken several measures to effect change 
in this area, including free enrolment in the NHIS for pregnant women, more must be done. 
In section VI, the Special Rapporteur commends Ghana on its efforts to reduce the spread 
of malaria, however, further progress can be made in this area by addressing the underlying 
determinants of health that contribute to the spread of this disease. Section VII deals with 
issues relating to environmental and occupational health. There are significant issues 
regarding occupational health and safety in Ghana, particularly in the mining sector, which 
the Government should urgently address. 
</p>
<p>The final section contains conclusions and recommendations on the right to mental 
and physical health in Ghana. 
</p>
<p> </p>

<p><b>A/HRC/20/15/Add.1 
</b></p>
